# bad_paths
# =========
# One active Perl regular expression per line, matched against the complete
# Path header.  Path tokens are separated by an exclamation mark (!).
#
# All examples are commented out and therefore inactive.  Remove the leading
# "# " only after copying a real Path header into a test file and verifying the
# expression with cleanfeed-admin.pl.
#
# Exact token at any position:
# (?:^|!)bad-transit\.example(?:!|$)
#
# Why the boundaries matter:
#   bad-transit\.example
# also matches "not-bad-transit.example.net".  The (?:^|!) and (?:!|$)
# alternatives require a complete Path token.
#
# A numbered farm, for example reader1, reader27, reader300:
# (?:^|!)reader[0-9]+\.abusive-provider\.example(?:!|$)
#
# One of several exact transit names:
# (?:^|!)(?:feed-a|feed-b|feed-c)\.example\.net(?:!|$)
#
# A literal .POSTED marker attached to one exact host:
# (?:^|!)reader12\.example\.net\.POSTED(?:!|$)
#
# A bounded hexadecimal identifier used by a broken gateway:
# (?:^|!)gateway-[A-Fa-f0-9]{8}\.example(?:!|$)
#
# Do not use generic fragments such as "news", "reader", "posted", or
# ".*example.*".  Path-based rejection is immediate and broad matches can cut
# off an entire legitimate feed.
